# Option A — Atlas connection string (paste from Atlas → Connect → Drivers)
# Use either mongodb+srv://… or the "standard" mongodb://host1:27017,host2:27017,… URI (often fixes TLS issues).
# Replace USER/PASSWORD; URL-encode the password if it contains @ : / ? # [ ] etc.
# Add retryWrites + write concern if missing: …&retryWrites=true&w=majority
MONGODB_URI=

# Option B — split credentials (Netlify / CI friendly; password can contain special chars)
# MONGODB_USER=
# MONGODB_PASSWORD=
# MONGODB_HOST=cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net
# Optional; default admin (Atlas database users usually authenticate here)
# MONGODB_AUTH_SOURCE=admin

# Optional database name (default: mongodb_dx_copilot)
MONGODB_DB_NAME=

# TLS to Atlas (OpenSSL "tlsv1 alert internal error"): app prefers IPv4 DNS order + IPv4 sockets.
# MONGODB_DNS_FAMILY=auto — use Node defaults (e.g. local Mongo on IPv6-only localhost).
# MONGODB_DNS_ORDER=verbatim — skip dns.setDefaultResultOrder("ipv4first").
# If TLS still fails, paste Atlas "standard connection string" (mongodb://host:27017,...) into MONGODB_URI instead of mongodb+srv://.
# The app marks `mongodb` as a server external in next.config.mjs so the driver is not webpack-bundled (avoids broken TLS in serverless).
